 Implementation will be achieved through management and organizational commitment, allocation of sufficient human and capital resources, and rigorous measurement and corrective systems."  Each location will "implement accident prevention, product stewardship, distribution, occupational health, pollution control, and community outreach programs designed to safeguard employees, visitors, customers, and the public from injuries and health hazards, to protect the environment and Westlake's assets, and maintain continuity of operations."



Both WLC and TXO use a safety process that includes six main steps to prevent accidental releases: 

-    Hazard identification, prevention, and control;

-    Safe design and construction;

-    Safety and health education and training;

-    Employee involvement, accountability, and responsibility;

-    Inspection, testing, repair, and preventative maintenance (mechanical integrity); and

-    Systematic evaluation for continual improvement.



II. Description of Stationary Source and Regulated Substances Handled



Stationary Source Description



Within the Sabine Industrial District, WLC produces polyethylene plastics and Epolene(R) waxes for industrial customer use in the manufacture of a variety of consumer and commercial products.  Since its beginning, WLC has integrated its safety and emergency response practices and processes with those of TXO. Prior to the initial Risk Management Program (RMP) submittal in October 2014, WLC was considered part of the TXO plant site for purposes of compliance with RMP.  In the event of an emergency, TXO provides emergency response services and coordination with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC).  These support services did not change because of the independent RMP submittal; WLC continues to work closely with TXO to ensure a safe work environment and effective emergency response, if needed.



